Rating: 4
What a simple wonderful dinner that my husband and I both loved! I did use only 1/4 cup of water as others reccommended for the Mustard-Dill Sauce. The Zucchini pickles are a must and complement the pork perfectly and so easy to make! Used 2 packages of dill to get the amount needed for the recipe. I also basted the pork with the sauce while grilling and still had plenty of sauce for serving. It did take less than an hour to make. Love it, love it!

Rating: 3
This recipe was delicious, my husband, 3-year old daughter, and I enjoyed it. Per previous review recommendations I held with water from the sauce. We decided the flavor of the sauce was strong and potent. If serving to guests who tastes I'm not sure of, in the future I will spread the sauce on the tenderloin with each turn on the grill rather than serve with the finished product.

Rating: 4
The true highlight of this dish is the part that's not in the title - the zucchini pickles! They take just 10 minutes to make. The pickles are amazing, and I'll be making them all summer as a side. I reviewed this recipe on my own blog, Recipes That Worked by Mandy Higgins.

Rating: 3
This was my first time cooking pork tenderloin and it definitely won't be my last! The flavours combine beautifully. I followed the recipe with two exceptions: rather than adding water to the sauce, I added a few tablespoons of yoghurt, and I used the sauce as a marinade for the pork. The results were lovely. Please, please, please, do not skimp on the zucchini pickles! They are fantastic, and they make the dish, in my opinion. They also transform the sandwiches of leftover pork the next day into something amazing.

Rating: 4
I didn't make the zucchini, but the Pork was excellent. I took the advice of others and reduced the water in the mustard/dill sauce to 1/4 cup. I also used it as a marinade. I turned the pork every 5 minutes on the grill and applied a new layer of marinade.

